Hi friend :)

I'd like to add a gitolite source and wanted to run the approach by you before sending a PR. A couple questions:

1. For getting the list of repositories, seems like the only way provided via the gitolite API itself is [the `info` command](http://gitolite.com/gitolite/user/#the-info-command). It provides a handy `-json` flag, e.g.:
   ```
   $ ssh git@git.mycompany.com info -json
   {
      "repos" : {
         "a_repo" : {
            "perms" : {
               "W" : 1,
               "R" : 1
            }
         },
         "some_repo-DEPRECATED" : {
            "perms" : {
               # "W" key is omitted entirely
               "R" : 1
            }
         }
      }
      "gitolite_version" : "1.2.3",
      "USER" : "git@somehost",
      "GL_USER" : "ckuehl",
      "git_version" : "1.2.3"
   }
   ```

   Potentially we could provide other ways to get this list (e.g. something like y/gits), but I'm thinking if I wanted to do that, I'd just format that into a JSON file and use the JSON file source.

   So, does over SSH sound okay? And if so, do you prefer subprocessing out to ssh or using paramiko? (I think I prefer the subprocess approach just to avoid adding a new dep?)

2. Actually I guess I only had one question. This looks pretty straightforward to implement :P

I can't seem to get the icons working with a Rails 4.1 app.

    #Gemfile:
    gem 'bootstrap-sass'   #3.2.0


    #application.css.scss:
    @import "bootstrap-sprockets";
    @import "bootstrap";


I get a `Sprockets::FileNotFound` error: `couldn't find file 'bootstrap/glyphicons-halflings-regular.eot'`

If I remove the `@import "bootstrap-sprockets";` line, then the error goes away, but the the icons don't work.

The only solution is to copy the fonts into my `app/assets/fonts` directory.


Anyone else having the same issue?

Further to #679, the package cache should be made read-only.  Since users will typically view any package files through the "lens" of an environment, editing some files in an environment would reasonably be assumed to be "isolated" to the environment itself.  Due to file linking this will (typically) not be the case, so besides better documentation (both for package creators and end users), we should set package files (probably not directories) to be read-only as a defensive measure.

It is a whole other can of worms, but at some point conda `install` and `create` may need an option like `--write` that will install a real copy of a package (instead of file links) that a user can edit without impact on other environments.  Whether this would be recursive to dependencies or not is a major consideration.

